nternet and public policy | journal = [[Policy & Internet]] | volume = 1 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u201321 | doi = 10.2202/1944-2866.1029 | date = December 2009 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last = Margetts | first = Helen | title = The internet and transparency | journal = [[The Political Quarterly]] | volume = 82 | issue = 4 | pages = 518\u2013521 | doi = 10.1111/j.1467-923X.2011.02253.x | date = October\u2013December 2011 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = Margetts | first1 = Helen Z. | last2 = John | first2 = Peter | last3 = Escher | first3 = Tobias | last4 = Reissfelder | first4 = St\u00e9phane | title = Social information and political participation on the internet: an experiment | journal = [[European Political Science Review]] | volume = 3 | issue = 3 | pages = 321\u2013344 | doi = 10.1017/S1755773911000129 | date = November 2011 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last = Margetts | first = Helen Z. | title = Experiments for public management research | journal = Public Management Review | volume = 13 | issue = 2 | pages = 189\u2013208 | doi = 10.1080/14719037.2010.532970 | date = 2011 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = Margetts | first1 = Helen | last2 = Dunleavy | first2 = Patrick | author-link2 = Patrick Dunleavy | title = The second wave of digital-era governance: a quasi-paradigm for government on the Web | journal = Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society A | volume = 371 | issue = 1987 | pages = 0382 | doi = 10.1098/rsta.2012.0382 | pmid = 23419851 | date = February 2013 | ref = harv | bibcode = 2013RSPTA.37120382M | doi-access = free }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = Margetts | first1 = Helen Z. | last2 = John | first2 = Peter | last3 = Hale | first3 = Scott A. | last4 = Reissfelder | first4 = St\u00e9phane | title = Leadership without leaders? Starters and followers in online collective action | journal = [[Political Studies (journal)|Political Studies]] | volume = 63 | issue = 2 | page = 277 | doi = 10.1111/1467-9248.12211 | date = June 2015 | ref = harv | arxiv = 1308.0237 }}\n\n;Papers\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = Margetts | first1 = Helen Z. | last2 = John | first2 = Peter | last3 = Hale | first3 = Scott A. | last4 = Yasseri | first4 = Taha | title = Investigating political participation and social information using big data and a natural experiment | journal = [[American Political Science Association|APSA 2014 Annual Meeting Paper]] | publisher = [[American Political Science Association]] | date = 2014 | arxiv = 1408.3562 | bibcode = 2014arXiv1408.3562H | ssrn = 2454570 | ref = harv }}\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2003 Margetts and [[Patrick Dunleavy]] were presented with the 'Political Scientists Making a Difference' award by the UK Policy Studies Association, in recognition for their work on a series of policy reports assessing the state of Government on the Internet for the UK [[National Audit Office (United Kingdom)|National Audit Office]].<ref name=\"oii\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/associates/helen-margetts.html Profile: Helen Margetts] Department of Politics and International Relations, University of Oxford\n* [http://www.oii.ox.ac.uk/people/?id=2 Profile: Helen Margetts] Oxford Internet Institute (OII), University of Oxford\n\n{{Subject bar | portal1=Philosophy | portal2=Society| portal3=Politics | portal4=Internet | portal5=University of Oxford | portal6=Biography | portal7=United Kingdom }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Margetts, Helen}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Mansfield College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:British political philosophers]]\n[[Category:British political scientists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox scholar|name=Helen Margetts|image=Helen Margetts.JPG|imagesize=220px|alt=|caption=Helen Margetts in Oxford|fullname=|othernames=|birth_name=Helen Zerlina Margetts|birth_date={{Birth date and age|df=yes|1961|09|15}}|birth_place=|death_date=<!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}}  -->|death_place=|death_cause=|nationality=[[United Kingdom|British]]|residence=|era=|region=|workplaces=|alma_mater=[[London School of Economics and Political Science]]|thesis_title=Computerisation in American and British central government 1975-95: policy-making, internal regulation and contracting in information technology|thesis_url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/556741174|thesis_year=1996|doctoral_advisor=|doctoral_students=|notable_students=|school_tradition=|main_interests=[[Political science]]|principal_ideas=|major_works=|awards=''Political Scientists Making a Difference'' (with [[Patrick Dunleavy]]) by the UK Policy Studies Association|influences=|influenced=|website=http://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/associates/helen-margetts.html|footnotes=|honorific_suffix=OBE FBA}}\n'''Helen Zerlina Margetts'''<ref name=Doctorate>{{cite thesis | degree = Ph.D. | last = Margetts | first = Helen Zerlina | date = 1996 | title = Computerisation in American and British central government 1975-95: policy-making, internal regulation and contracting in information technology |publisher= [[University of London]] | oclc = 556741174 }}</ref> {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%||OBE|FBA}} (born 15 September 1961),<ref name=Congress>{{cite web |title= Margetts, Helen |url= http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/no94002890.html |publisher= Library of Congress |accessdate= 31 August 2016 |quote= data sheet (b. 9-15-1961) }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = Who's Who|last = |first = |publisher = |date = November 2015|isbn = 9780199540884|location = |pages = |chapter = MARGETTS, Helen Zerlina}}</ref> is Professor of Internet and Society at the [[Oxford Internet Institute]] (OII), [[University of Oxford]] and from 2011 to 2018 was Director of the OII. She is currently Director of the Public Policy Programme at The [[Alan Turing Institute]]. She is a [[political science|political scientist]] specialising in [[Information Age|digital era]] governance and [[politics]], and has published over a hundred books, journal articles and research reports in this field.\n\n== Career ==\nMargetts obtained her first degree, a [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] in mathematics, from the [[University of Bristol]].<ref name=\"oii\"/> In her early career she was a computer programmer and [[systems analyst]] with [[Rank Xerox]],<ref name=\"guardian\">{{Cite news|title = IT news|url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2004/apr/29/onlinesupplement.insideit1|newspaper = The Guardian|date = 28 April 2004|access-date = 20 January 2016 |issn = 0261-3077|language = en-GB|first = Jack|last = Schofield|first2 = Eric|last2 = Doyle|first3 = S. A.|last3 = Mathieson}}</ref><ref name=\"oii\"/> after which she took up postgraduate study at the [[London School of Economics]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Helen Margetts {{!}} Associate Members {{!}} Academic {{!}} Profiles|url = http://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/associates/helen-margetts.html|website = www.politics.ox.ac.uk | publisher = [[University of Oxford]]|access-date = 20 January 2016}}</ref> There she earned a [[Master of Science|MSc]] in Politics and Public Policy (awarded in 1990) and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in Government (in 1996).<ref name=\":0\" /> From 1994 to 1999 she lectured at [[Birkbeck College, London]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMargetts is Professor of Internet and Society at the [[University of Oxford]],<ref name=\"oii\">{{cite web | title = Professor Helen Margetts | url = http://www.oii.ox.ac.uk/people/?id=2 | website = oii.ox.ac.uk | publisher = [[Oxford Internet Institute]] |accessdate= 20 January 2016 }}</ref> a fellow of [[Mansfield College, Oxford|Mansfield College]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mansfield.ox.ac.uk/index.php/professor-helen-margetts |title=Professor Helen Margetts  |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Mansfield College, Oxford |access-date=1 July 2019 |quote=}}</ref> and from 2011 to 2018 was Director of the [[Oxford Internet Institute]] (OII). Prior to joining the OII in October 2004, she was a Professor in Political Science and Director of the Public Policy Programme at [[University College London]].<ref name=\"guardian\" /><ref>{{Cite web|title =Digital Advisory Board profile - Professor Helen Margetts |publisher=Government Digital Service|url = https://gds.blog.gov.uk/profileprofessorhelenmargetts/|website = gds.blog.gov.uk|access-date = 20 January 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAmongst her research projects at the OII, she has used a variety of methods to investigate how the Internet can affect the relationship between citizens and government, and how informational cues can affect the success of online petitions and charity fundraising.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Encyclopedia of Social Media and Politics|chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qS91AwAAQBAJ|publisher = SAGE Publications|date = 20 December 2013|isbn = 9781452290263|language = en|first = Amanda|last = Clarke|pages = 938|chapter = Oxford Internet Institute|editor-first = Kerric|editor-last = Harvey}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = First day 'is crucial for success of e-petitions'|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-23441223|website = BBC News|access-date = 20 January 2016|first = Ed|last = Lowther|date = 4 September 2013}}</ref> In March 2011 she was an expert witness for the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]'s [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]]'s investigation into the cost of publicly funded information technology projects.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Government and IT - a Recipe for Rip-offs: Time for a New Approach, Twelfth Report of Session 2010-11, Vol. 2: Oral and Written Evidence|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=WUgVhui46FcC|publisher = The Stationery Office|date = 28 July 2011|isbn = 9780215561077|language = en|first = Great Britain: Parliament: House of Commons: Public Administration Select|last = Committee}}</ref>\n\nMargetts is a Fellow of The [[Alan Turing Institute]] and is currently Director of the Public Policy Programme at the institute.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.turing.ac.uk/people/programme-directors/helen-margetts |title=Professor Helen Margetts OBE |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Alan Turing Institute |access-date=1 July 2019 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nMargetts holds many advisory positions, including sitting on the UK Government's Digital Economy Council, the Home Office Scientific Advisory Council, and (from 2011-2015) the Government Digital Advisory Board.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Introducing the Digital Advisory Board {{!}} Government Digital Service|url = https://gds.blog.gov.uk/2012/04/25/introducing-the-digital-advisory-board/|access-date = 20 January 2016 |date = 25 April 2012|publisher = |website = GOV.UK|last = Lane Fox|first = Martha|authorlink = Martha Lane Fox, Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Digital Advisory Board to support Government Digital Service (Wired UK)|url = https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-04/24/digital-advisory-board-gds|website = Wired UK|publisher = |access-date = 20 January 2016|last = Solon|first = Olivia|date = 25 April 2012|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160310063506/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-04/24/digital-advisory-board-gds|archive-date = 10 March 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Government launches Digital Advisory Board|url = http://www.computerweekly.com/news/2240149027/Government-launches-Digital-Advisory-Board|website = ComputerWeekly|access-date = 20 January 2016 |language = en-GB|date = 25 April 2012|last = Hall|first = Kathleen}}</ref>\n\nShe was appointed an [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2019 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/62507/supplement/N1|title=2019 New Year Honours List|date=29 Dec 2018|website=The London Gazette|access-date=28 Dec 2018}}</ref> In July 2019 she was elected as a Fellow of the [[British Academy]].<ref name=\"FBA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/sites/default/files/New%20Fellows%202019_0.pdf |title=New Fellows 2019 |publisher=[[British Academy]] |accessdate=2019-07-21 }}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n;Books\nMargetts has co-authored a series of books which have helped to define the field of digital-era governance:\n* {{cite book | editor-last1 = Margetts | editor-first1 = Helen | editor-last2 = Smyth | editor-first2 = Gareth | title = Turning Japanese?: Britain with a permanent party of government | publisher = Lawrence & Wishart | location = London | year = 1994 | isbn = 9780853157854 }}\n* {{cite thesis | degree = Ph.D. | last = Margetts | first = Helen Zerlina | date = 1996 | title = Computerisation in American and British central government 1975-95: policy-making, internal regulation and contracting in information technology |publisher= [[University of London]] | oclc = 556741174 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Margetts | first = Helen | title = Information technology in government: Britain and America | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | year = 1999 | isbn = 9780203208038 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Margetts | first1 = Helen | last2 = Dowding | first2 = Keith | last3 = Hughes | first3 = James | author-link2 = Keith Dowding | author-link3 = Jim Hughes (academic) | title = Challenges to democracy: ideas, involvement, and institutions | series = The Political Studies Association Yearbook 2000 | publisher = Palgrave | location = Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire New York | year = 2001 | isbn = 9780333789827 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Margetts | first1 = Helen | last2 = Dunleavy | first2 = Patrick | last3 = Weir | first3 = Stuart | last4 = Trevor | first4 